{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c1d35381-ae1f-47d7-a2ec-090af1335802","content":"Good news — in .NET 10, `dotnet test` uses Microsoft Testing Platform **by default**. The `TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport` property was a .NET 9 opt-in and is now unnecessary. You can safely remove it.\n\nYour project just needs:\n- `EnableMSTestRunner` → already set ✅\n- `OutputType` as `Exe` → already set ✅\n\nWant me to remove the redundant property from your csproj?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"08d5b8b2-22e9-46f6-88d0-b2415c567583","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is on .NET 10 SDK (10.0.100) and wants to know about MTP support. Let me provide accurate guidance.\n\nIn .NET 10, `dotnet test` natively uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP) as the default test runner. The `TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport` property is no longer needed — it was a .NET 9 opt-in flag to enable MTP support in `dotnet test`. In .NET 10, this is the default behavior.\n\nSo they can remove `<TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>` as it's no longer necessary.\n\n\nThe `<EnableMSTestRunner>true</EnableMSTestRunner>` property they have is still required though — that's what makes the test project an executable using MTP. I should let them know they can safely drop the old property while keeping this one, and offer to help clean up their project file.","outputTokens":340,"requestId":"0429:1C1C65:1E5231B:2226FE4:69E81AC2"},"id":"9b9d4acf-ac2d-436c-97fc-ffc529579ba7","timestamp":"2026-04-22T00:48:10.381Z","parentId":"e5193f6b-ed5f-4203-bd60-0085b6e436eb"}
